First, let's consider the structure of a 4x4 matrix after fixing the first pivot to be 1 through row operations. The matrix will look something like this after normalization:

\[
\begin{pmatrix}
1 & a_{12} & a_{13} & a_{14} \\
0 & b_{22} & b_{23} & b_{24} \\
0 & c_{32} & c_{33} & c_{34} \\
0 & d_{42} & d_{43} & d_{44}
\end{pmatrix}
\]

Here, \(a_{ij}\), \(b_{ij}\), \(c_{ij}\), and \(d_{ij}\) are random variables uniformly distributed over [0, 1]. We are interested in the expected value of the absolute value of the second pivot, which is \(|b_{22}|\). Since \(b_{22}\) is uniformly distributed over [0, 1], its absolute value is simply \(b_{22}\).

